- cs.CR (Cryptography and Security): The paper discusses the risks associated with the Libra blockchain, including financial and technological risks, which are relevant to the field of cryptography and security. The paper also addresses the regulatory challenges of the project, which may require cryptographic solutions to ensure privacy and security.
- cs.CY (Computers and Society): The paper discusses the ethical and political implications of the Libra project, including issues related to national sovereignty, financial inclusion, and data privacy. These topics are relevant to the field of computers and society, which studies the social and ethical impacts of technology.
- cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory): The paper describes the governance structure of the Libra project, which involves a set of rules and protocols that define the behavior of the Libra blockchain. This topic is relevant to the field of formal languages and automata theory, which studies the properties and behavior of formal systems.
- cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory): The paper discusses the incentives and motivations of the various stakeholders involved in the Libra project, including Facebook, the Libra Association, and the users of the Libra blockchain. This topic is relevant to the field of computer science and game theory, which studies the strategic behavior of agents in complex systems.
- cs.SE (Software Engineering): The paper discusses the technical challenges of implementing the Libra blockchain
